---
import Footer from "../../components/Footer.astro";
import Nav from "../../components/Nav.astro";
import SiteLayout from "../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const title = "Case Study: Agent-fleet — Harness Health";
const description =
  "A Harness Health case study showing how repeated test-command re-asks become durable project guidance.";
---

<SiteLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <Nav />
  <main id="main">
    <article class="article-page">
      <header class="article-hero">
        <div class="container section-narrow">
          <span class="eyebrow">Case study</span>
          <h1>Agent-fleet stopped re-learning the same test command.</h1>
          <p class="lead">
            A small missing hint created repeated friction. Harness Health
            caught the pattern, explained the user and agent benefit, and turned
            it into a measurable improvement.
          </p>
        </div>
      </header>

      <div class="container article-grid">
        <aside class="article-aside card">
          <img
            src="/story-standing-desk.png"
            alt=""
            loading="lazy"
            decoding="async"
            class="aside-image"
          />
          <span class="mono">Result</span>
          <strong>4 repeated prompts targeted</strong>
          <p>Suggested fix: add the exact test command to AGENTS.md.</p>
        </aside>

        <div class="article-body">
          <h2>The signal</h2>
          <p>
            In several sessions, the agent guessed the validation command,
            failed, and needed the user to redirect it. The raw mistake was
            small. The repeated shape was the important part.
          </p>

          <h2>The health report</h2>
          <p>
            Harness Health framed the finding as an improvement instead of a
            scolding: add the test command where the harness already looks for
            project guidance. The agent benefit is fewer guesses. The user
            benefit is fewer prompts that say, effectively, “run the actual
            tests.”
          </p>

          <h2>The follow-up</h2>
          <p>
            The next review keeps watching the same metric. If re-asks drop
            without raising token cost or tool failures, the habit stays. If the
            signal weakens, the suggestion can be snoozed or revised.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>
  </main>
  <Footer />
</SiteLayout>
